// The single ensures of `insert` is `self@ == old(self)@.insert(key@, value)`.
// Applied to the two runs, both `post*_self_@` are equal to the same
// `pre_self_@.insert(key@, value)` term, so transitivity collapses them.
// We make this implication explicit (LHS = the two ensures, RHS = the
// HashMap views coincide) so z3 doesn't have to bridge it through the
// `Map::insert` axioms across the two runs. We also lift the equality
// to `=~=` in case `det_insert_equal` is phrased with map extensionality.
assert((post1_self_@ == pre_self_@.insert(key@, value)
        && post2_self_@ == pre_self_@.insert(key@, value))
       ==> post1_self_@ == post2_self_@);
assert((post1_self_@ == pre_self_@.insert(key@, value)
        && post2_self_@ == pre_self_@.insert(key@, value))
       ==> post1_self_@ =~= post2_self_@);
